#
# WHAT IS cli-progress AND WHY IS IT THE 47TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# cli-progress (https://github.com/npkgz/cli-progress, 1252+ stars)
# is **npkgz (Andi Dittrich)'s ":hourglass: easy to use progress-
# bar for command-line/terminal applications"** — a TypeScript-Node
# progress-bar library that supports BOTH single-bar AND multi-bar
# modes via two distinct classes:
#
#   * `SingleBar` — displays one progress bar, classic ora-like
#                    rendering
#   * `MultiBar`  — displays N progress bars in a synchronized
#                    container, similar to Go's vbauerster/mpb or
#                    Rust's indicatif MultiProgress
#
# Andi Dittrich is a German Node.js developer; cli-progress was
# created in 2017 as a polished progress-bar alternative to the
# original `progress` npm package (visionmedia/node-progress) which
# had been unmaintained since 2017 and lacked multi-bar support.
# cli-progress has been actively maintained for 8 years.
#
# cli-progress's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. SINGLE-OR-MULTI BAR MODES VIA TWO CLASSES — cli-progress
#      exposes both modes via separate exported classes rather than
#      one configurable class:
#
#          import { SingleBar, MultiBar, Presets } from 'cli-progress';
#
#          // Single bar
#          const bar = new SingleBar({
#              format: '{bar} | {percentage}% | {value}/{total}',
#          }, Presets.shades_classic);
#          bar.start(100, 0);
#          for (let i = 0; i <= 100; i++) {
#              await sleep(10);
#              bar.update(i);
#          }
#          bar.stop();
#
#          // Multi bar
#          const multibar = new MultiBar({
#              clearOnComplete: false,
#              hideCursor: true,
#              format: '{bar} {filename} | {percentage}% | {value}/{total}',
#          }, Presets.shades_grey);
#          const bar1 = multibar.create(200, 0, {filename: 'file1.txt'});
#          const bar2 = multibar.create(1000, 0, {filename: 'file2.txt'});
#          // ... update bar1 and bar2 concurrently ...
#          multibar.stop();
#
#      Compare:
#         * ora R524:       single spinner only (no multi)
#         * listr2 R556:    task tree (different abstraction)
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): both modes in ONE library via
#                                    same class hierarchy
#         * mpb R559 (Go): multi-only library
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with explicit
#      SingleBar + MultiBar class separation.
#
#   2. PRESETS CATALOG — cli-progress ships with a `Presets` object
#      containing pre-configured visual styles:
#         * `Presets.legacy`         — old-style ASCII bar ====>
#         * `Presets.shades_classic` — Unicode block-shading
#                                       ▓▒░ light/medium/dark
#         * `Presets.shades_grey`    — Unicode block-shading in
#                                       greyscale
#         * `Presets.rect`            — solid rectangle ▮▯
#      Apps select a preset rather than configuring bar characters
#      individually.  Compare:
#         * ora R524: spinners (cli-spinners has 80+ named styles)
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): ProgressStyle.template() with
#                                    explicit character config
#         * mpb R559 (Go): decorator pattern (no presets)
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with named-preset
#      catalog for bar visual styles.
#
#   3. FORMAT TEMPLATE WITH PAYLOAD INTERPOLATION — cli-progress
#      uses a template-string format where you reference variables
#      with `{var}` syntax:
#
#          new SingleBar({
#              format: 'Progress |{bar}| {percentage}% | ETA: {eta}s '
#                       + '| {value}/{total} | {filename} | {speed}',
#          });
#          // Later:
#          bar.update(50, { filename: 'image.jpg', speed: '5 MB/s' });
#
#      Built-in template vars: `{bar}`, `{percentage}`, `{value}`,
#      `{total}`, `{eta}` (seconds), `{eta_formatted}` (h:m:s),
#      `{duration}`, `{duration_formatted}`.  User-defined vars via
#      payload object passed to `bar.update(value, payload)`.
#      Compare:
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): {bar} {pos}/{len} {percent}
#                                    template syntax
#         * mpb R559 (Go): Decorator pattern (no templates)
#         * cli-progress: template-string with built-in + payload
#                          interpolation
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with template-
#      string + payload-interpolation formatting.
#
#   4. NO-TTY GRACEFUL DEGRADATION — When stdout is NOT a TTY (e.g.,
#      piped to a file, CI environment), cli-progress's `noTTYOutput:
#      false` option (default true) makes the library FALLBACK to
#      LINE-BUFFERED OUTPUT instead of escape-sequence-based animated
#      bars.  This means logs from CI runs containing cli-progress
#      output don't fill with `\r` carriage-return spam.  Compare:
#         * ora R524: has isEnabled option to disable spinners
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): is_term auto-detection
#         * mpb R559 (Go): manual rendering-disable flag
#         * cli-progress: noTTYOutput option with line-buffered
#                          fallback by default
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with explicit
#      no-TTY graceful-degradation mode.
#
#   5. SPEED + ETA DERIVATIVE TRACKING — cli-progress computes:
#         * Current speed (items per second) from sliding window
#         * Average speed since start
#         * ETA from current+average speed combination
#         * Lap time (time since last update)
#      All computed automatically; available via template vars or
#      `bar.getProgress()` introspection.  Compare:
#         * mpb R559 (Go): EwmaETA decorator for ETA only
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): {eta_precise} template var
#         * cli-progress: full derivative tracking including
#                          current-speed + average-speed + ETA +
#                          lap-time
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with comprehensive
#      derivative tracking (speed + ETA + lap-time).
#
# cli-progress's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI
# libraries:
#
#   * Like ora R524     — progress-display axis (same axis,
#                          different mode: ora is spinner; cli-
#                          progress is bar)
#   * Like listr2 R556   — multi-operation display (same axis,
#                          different abstraction: listr2 is tasks;
#                          cli-progress is bars)
#   * Like chalk R528    — uses ANSI escapes
#   * Like clipanion     — sisi uses both cli-progress + clipanion
#                          together
#   * Unlike all of the above — SingleBar + MultiBar class
#                                separation + Presets catalog +
#                                template-format + no-TTY fallback +
#                                full derivative tracking.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    indicatif R522 (single library covering both
#                     single + multi modes)
#         * Go:      vbauerster/mpb R559 (multi-only library;
#                     cheggaaa/pb R523 for single)
#     cli-progress completes the MULTI-OPERATION-DISPLAY triple
#     across the top three languages, with TS-Node having THE
#     WIDEST progress-axis coverage at three documented libraries
#     (ora + listr2 + cli-progress).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE sisi CLI — clipanion + cli-progress Composition
#
# sisi's argv parser is `arcanis/clipanion` (already documented in
# the taxonomy at earlier round):
#
#     import { Builtins, Cli, Command, Option } from 'clipanion';
#
#     export class IndexCommand extends Command {
#         static paths = [ [ 'index' ] ];
#         target = Option.String();
#         async execute() {
#             await index(this.target);
#         }
#     }
#
#     export class SearchCommand extends Command {
#         static paths = [ [ 'search' ] ];
#         query = Option.String();
#         target = Option.String('--in');
#         max = Option.String('--max', '20');
#         print = Option.Boolean('--print');
#         async execute() {
#             const results = await search(this.query, {
#                 maxResults: parseInt(this.max),
#                 targetDir: this.target,
#             });
#             ...
#         }
#     }
#
# Four subcommands (index, search, list-index, remove-index).
# During `sisi index`, cli-progress renders a SingleBar showing
# image-indexing progress (one tick per image processed through
# CLIP embedding computation).
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. SINGLE-OR-MULTI BAR MODES VIA TWO CLASSES — Every other
#      documented TS-Node CLI library uses one class per mode (ora
#      is single-spinner only).  cli-progress exposes BOTH modes via
#      `SingleBar` and `MultiBar` classes.  FIRST documented TS-
#      Node CLI library with explicit single+multi class separation.
#
#   2. PRESETS CATALOG — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library uses explicit configuration.  cli-progress ships
#      with a `Presets` object containing named pre-configured
#      visual styles.  FIRST documented TS-Node progress library
#      with named-preset catalog.
#
#   3. FORMAT TEMPLATE WITH PAYLOAD INTERPOLATION — Every other
#      documented TS-Node progress library uses fixed formats or
#      method-based configuration.  cli-progress uses template
#      strings with built-in + user-payload variable interpolation.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node progress library with template-
#      string + payload formatting.
#
#   4. NO-TTY GRACEFUL DEGRADATION — Every other documented TS-Node
#      CLI library either disables itself entirely in CI or floods
#      logs with \r carriage returns.  cli-progress's `noTTYOutput:
#      false` option defaults to line-buffered fallback.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node CLI library with explicit no-TTY
#      graceful-degradation mode.
#
#   5. FULL DERIVATIVE TRACKING — Every other documented TS-Node
#      progress library computes either no derivatives or just ETA.
#      cli-progress computes current-speed, average-speed, ETA, and
#      lap-time automatically.  FIRST documented TS-Node progress
#      library with comprehensive derivative tracking.
#
